------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£ Question 1 ‚Äì Convert Lowercase Letter to Uppercase
------------------------------------------------------------

üîπ Problem Statement

You are given a single character as input.

‚Ä¢ Input will be a lowercase letter (a to z)
‚Ä¢ You must print its corresponding uppercase letter

Examples:

Input   Output
a       A
b       B
c       C
t       T


------------------------------------------------------------
2Ô∏è‚É£ Thought Process (VERY IMPORTANT)
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher asks the class:

‚ÄúIf I give you character 'a', how will you convert it to 'A'?‚Äù

Most students answer:
‚Ä¢ if-else
‚Ä¢ switch case
‚Ä¢ hardcoded mapping

Teacher immediately stops them ‚ùå

‚ÄúThis is NOT scalable.‚Äù

Imagine:
‚Ä¢ 26 letters
‚Ä¢ Then symbols
‚Ä¢ Then multiple conversions

We need **LOGIC**, not hardcoding.


------------------------------------------------------------
ASCII Logic (CORE IDEA)
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher introduces ASCII thinking.

Facts:
‚Ä¢ ASCII of 'a' = 97
‚Ä¢ ASCII of 'A' = 65
‚Ä¢ Difference = 32

But teacher says:
‚ÄúDon‚Äôt remember numbers. Remember relationships.‚Äù

Correct formula:

Uppercase = (lowercase - 'a') + 'A'

Why does this work?

'a' - 'a' = 0
'b' - 'a' = 1
'c' - 'a' = 2

Adding 'A' shifts it to uppercase.

This logic works for ALL letters.


------------------------------------------------------------
3Ô∏è‚É£ Why Use a Function Here?
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher asks:
‚ÄúCan we write this logic inside main?‚Äù

Yes ‚Äî but ‚ùå not recommended.

Why FUNCTION?

‚Ä¢ Logic written ONCE
‚Ä¢ Reusable
‚Ä¢ Clean code
‚Ä¢ Readable
‚Ä¢ Easy to debug
‚Ä¢ Interview-friendly

This is exactly WHY functions exist.


------------------------------------------------------------
4Ô∏è‚É£ Code ‚Äì Lowercase to Uppercase Using Function
------------------------------------------------------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Function to convert lowercase to uppercase
char convertToUpper(char ch)
{
    char result = (ch - 'a') + 'A';
    return result;
}

int main()
{
    char ch;
    cin >> ch;

    char answer = convertToUpper(ch);
    cout << answer;

    return 0;
}


------------------------------------------------------------
5Ô∏è‚É£ Dry Run Example
------------------------------------------------------------

Input:
h

Step-by-step:

'h' - 'a' = 7
'A' + 7 = 'H'

Output:
H


------------------------------------------------------------
6Ô∏è‚É£ Important Clarification ‚Äì main() is ALSO a Function
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher clears confusion:

Yes,
main() is also a function.

int main()

‚Ä¢ It returns int
‚Ä¢ return 0 ‚Üí successful execution

Modern compilers allow skipping:
return 0;

But internally:
return 0 still happens.


====================================================================
üî¢ Question 2 ‚Äì Armstrong Number (Using Functions)
====================================================================


------------------------------------------------------------
7Ô∏è‚É£ What is an Armstrong Number?
------------------------------------------------------------

Definition:

A number is Armstrong if:

Sum of each digit raised to the power of total digits
== original number

Example 1:
153

Digits = 3

1¬≥ + 5¬≥ + 3¬≥
= 1 + 125 + 27
= 153 ‚úÖ

Example 2:
23

Digits = 2

2¬≤ + 3¬≤ = 4 + 9 = 13 ‚ùå


------------------------------------------------------------
8Ô∏è‚É£ Breaking the Problem (Engineer Mindset)
------------------------------------------------------------

Teacher emphasizes:

‚ÄúNever solve big problems in one shot.‚Äù

Break it into TASKS.

Task 1:
‚Ä¢ Count number of digits

Task 2:
‚Ä¢ Check Armstrong condition

Each task = one function

This is called:
‚û°Ô∏è Problem Decomposition


------------------------------------------------------------
9Ô∏è‚É£ Function 1 ‚Äì Count Digits
------------------------------------------------------------

Logic:
‚Ä¢ Divide number by 10 repeatedly
‚Ä¢ Count until number becomes 0

int countDigits(int n)
{
    int count = 0;

    while (n > 0)
    {
        count++;
        n /= 10;
    }

    return count;
}


------------------------------------------------------------
üîü Function 2 ‚Äì Armstrong Check
------------------------------------------------------------

Logic:
‚Ä¢ Extract digits using % 10
‚Ä¢ Raise digit to power = number of digits
‚Ä¢ Add them
‚Ä¢ Compare with original number

We use inbuilt pow() function.

#include <cmath>

bool isArmstrong(int number, int digits)
{
    int original = number;
    int sum = 0;

    while (number > 0)
    {
        int digit = number % 10;
        sum += pow(digit, digits);
        number /= 10;
    }

    return sum == original;
}


------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ Main Program (Connecting Functions)
------------------------------------------------------------

int main()
{
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    int digits = countDigits(n);

    if (isArmstrong(n, digits))
        cout << 1;
    else
        cout << 0;

    return 0;
}


------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ Dry Run ‚Äì Input: 153
------------------------------------------------------------

countDigits(153)
‚Üí returns 3

isArmstrong(153, 3)

1¬≥ + 5¬≥ + 3¬≥ = 153

Condition true

Output:
1


